english:
  title: Prayer for Rain at the Circular Altar Sacrifice
  author: Byeon Gyeyrang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Alas! Heaven through yin and yang, through the five elements, gives birth to all things. Thus we say that Heaven and Earth are the parents of ten thousand things. As parents toward their children extend their care without limit—guiding them toward benefit and away from harm—so too does Heaven send forth rain and sunshine, heat and cold, taking turns through the seasons, that all creatures beneath heaven, great and small, fine and coarse, may fulfill their destinies. The Book of Changes teaches: "The way of Heaven transforms and changes; each thing realizes its nature and fulfills its destiny. Clouds move and rain falls; all things take form." This is what is meant.

    Yet though it is so, the ruler who receives the Mandate of Heaven above, who tends the countless people below—when human affairs move below, Heaven's responses manifest above. Therefore, reverence and peace, wisdom and noble counsel bring forth timely rains and sunshine, appropriate heat and cold and wind. But recklessness, presumption, indulgence, and confusion summon calamities and signs of misfortune.

    Now in this height of summer, we are struck by cruel drought. The fault lies with me—I cannot seek it elsewhere. Perhaps my punishments fall astray, and the guilty receive undeserved pardon while the innocent suffer calamity. Perhaps I have erred in what I keep and what I cast away, so that the loyal and honest are neglected while the cunning and flattering run rampant. Perhaps wisdom is clouded and the people's voice cannot reach above. Perhaps laws are changed in confusion and officials grow ignorant of their observance.

    What of the vastness I cannot see with my eyes, the regions I cannot reach with my ears? The provinces are broad, the people numerous. Many suffer under unequal burdens and cry out against the many forms of taxation. How many rise in resentment and wound the harmonious energy? All of this stems from my own want of virtue. Thus do I reproach myself within, endlessly.

    I have read the writings of sages and understand, however imperfectly, the duties that should guide a ruler. I have felt deeply the lessons of past ages. Therefore I have not surrendered to wine and women, nor lost myself in hunting and revelry that harms the treasury and injures the people. I do not squander the lives of soldiers in needless war. My only desire is to serve the greater powers with propriety, to serve Heaven with sincerity, to be sparing in my own comforts while generous to the people's welfare, diligent in hearing petitions while careful in administering justice. In every word, every gesture, every command I issue, I seek to align myself with the Way. Above, I would not betray the trust that Heaven has placed upon me. Below, I would comfort the billions who look to me. My anxious heart—Heaven surely sees it.

    Yet bound as I am by the nature I was born with, by desires of the flesh, by learning imperfectly pursued, how can I ensure that all my daily deeds conform to what is right? How can I avoid offending the mind of Heaven? How could I, preserving a single heart to serve Heaven, cultivating fear and reverence to serve the Highest, remain constant and unwavering in this reverence from dawn to dusk?

    It is fitting that Heaven's reproof falls heavy upon me. Who could I blame?

    And yet—Heaven's wisdom arises from the wisdom of the people. Above and below are connected without barrier. Thus even the poorest man who loses his way still cries out to Heaven. How much more so the ruler who stands over one nation, who tends countless millions! How much more so as a child toward a father, when urgency compels, would I not seek aid, regardless of my own worth?

    Moreover, because of me alone, all things wither and fade. How could this bring peace to the heart of Heaven?

    This drought has reached such extremity. I have already prayed to the spirits of mountain and stream, made offering at the altar of the gods of soil and grain, gone before the tablets of my ancestors. Yet still no answer comes. My sorrow burns like flame, sears like boiling water. At meals I forget to eat. Rising from my bed, I cannot rest. Day after day my fear deepens.

    How dare I not lay bare my heart, spill out my blood, and make clear declaration before the Lord of Heaven, beseeching protection and blessing?

    Thus I offer these humble gifts and lay bare my unworthy feelings. I humbly beseech the Lord of Heaven: Look upon my accumulated sincerity, examine the words I have spoken, forgive my offenses and errors, grant me your compassion. Let down rain like a downpour to revive all that has withered. Let the hundred grains come to harvest. Let the innocent countless people, all the flying and swimming creatures of creation, all living things receive the blessing of growth and life. I harbor this deepest of wishes.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The circular altar (圓壇) was a traditional structure used for imperial rain-bringing rituals, believed to connect earthly governance with celestial powers.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to yin-yang and five elements reflects classical Chinese cosmological understanding of how universal forces govern both nature and human society.
  - key: ''
    value: The citation from the Book of Changes (易經) represents the philosophical foundation for understanding the correspondence between human virtue and natural phenomena.
